results.name: a(n) is the number of the proper divisors of n that are Jacobsthal numbers (A001045).
link: Antti Karttunen, Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..21845
example: For n = 21, whose proper divisors are [1, 3, 7], both 1 and 3 are in A001045, thus a(21) = 2.
mathematica: With[{s = LinearRecurrence[{1, 2}, {0, 1}, 24]}, Table[DivisorSum[n, 1 &, And[MemberQ[s, #], # != n] &], {n, 105}]] (* _Michael De Vlieger_, Oct 09 2017 *)
